          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
            The Mandala Krama represents one of the most profound systems of
            sacred geometry in Eastern spiritual traditions. Dating back
            thousands of years, this intricate geometric pattern serves as both
            a meditation tool and a symbolic representation of the cosmos and
            consciousness itself.
          </p>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">
            Origins and Meaning
          </h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
            The word "Mandala" comes from Sanskrit, meaning "circle" or
            "completion." "Krama" refers to sequence or progression. Together,
            they describe the systematic unfolding of consciousness through
            geometric patterns. These patterns are believed to map the journey
            from the individual self to universal awareness.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-gray-50 p-6 rounded-lg mb-6">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-3">
              The Five Elements of Mandala Krama
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3">
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <div
                  class="w-6 h-6 flex items-center justify-center mr-2 mt-0.5 bg-primary/10 rounded-full"
                >
                  <i class="ri-fire-line text-primary"></i>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                    >Earth (Prithvi):</span
                  >
                  <span class="text-gray-700">
                    Represented by the square, symbolizing stability and
                    foundation.</span
                  >
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <div
                  class="w-6 h-6 flex items-center justify-center mr-2 mt-0.5 bg-primary/10 rounded-full"
                >
                  <i class="ri-water-flash-line text-primary"></i>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-medium text-gray-800">Water (Jala):</span>
                  <span class="text-gray-700">
                    Depicted as a crescent, representing flow and
                    adaptability.</span
                  >
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <div
                  class="w-6 h-6 flex items-center justify-center mr-2 mt-0.5 bg-primary/10 rounded-full"
                >
                  <i class="ri-sun-line text-primary"></i>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-medium text-gray-800">Fire (Agni):</span>
                  <span class="text-gray-700">
                    Shown as a triangle pointing upward, symbolizing
                    transformation.</span
                  >
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <div
                  class="w-6 h-6 flex items-center justify-center mr-2 mt-0.5 bg-primary/10 rounded-full"
                >
                  <i class="ri-cloud-windy-line text-primary"></i>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-medium text-gray-800">Air (Vayu):</span>
                  <span class="text-gray-700">
                    Represented by a circle, indicating movement and
                    expansion.</span
                  >
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="flex items-start">
                <div
                  class="w-6 h-6 flex items-center justify-center mr-2 mt-0.5 bg-primary/10 rounded-full"
                >
                  <i class="ri-space-ship-line text-primary"></i>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <span class="font-medium text-gray-800">Ether (Akasha):</span>
                  <span class="text-gray-700">
                    Depicted as a point or bindu at the center, representing
                    pure consciousness.</span
                  >
                </div>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-800 mb-4">
            Practical Applications
          </h2>
          <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
            The Mandala Krama is not merely a theoretical concept but a
            practical tool for spiritual development. Practitioners use it in
            various ways:
          </p>

